Transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs) are neurodegenerative disorders that occur in sheep (scrapie), cattle (bovine spongiform encephalopathy, BSE) and humans (Creutzfeldt to Jakob disease, CJD) and share similar characteristics: long incubation periods and a progressive and chronic clinical course resulting in death (Fraser, 1976 ). The accumulation of an abnormal isoform (PrPSc) of a normal cellular protein (PrPC) in organs from infected individuals correlates with the presence of infectivity
